  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions can be traced through several key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed historically\n- Initially addressed through tax evasion and banking regulations\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First comprehensive anti-money laundering legislation\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Mandated reporting of cash transactions over $10,000\n\n3. International Frameworks:\n- 1988 Vienna Convention against drug trafficking\n- 1989 establishment of Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones:\n- US Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- US Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations (RICO) Act\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - Expanded anti-money laundering provisions\n\n5. Global Expansion:\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Development of comprehensive regulatory frameworks\n- Expanded criminal penalties\n- Enhanced financial institution reporting requirements\n\n6. Modern Era:\n- Growing focus on cryptocurrency and digital transaction regulations\n- Increased technological sophistication in detection methods\n- Continued international collaboration against financial crimes\n\nThe legal framework continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and criminal strategies.",
